"""
MKT Context Commentary — Matthew chapters 18–20
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-matthew-18-20.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/matthew.json
- data/commentary/mkt-context/matthew.json (pre-existing stubs for 18:15, 19:1, 20:1)

Key decisions in this range:
- Ch18 community discipline procedure: Qumran 1QS 5:25-6:1 and CD 9:2-4 parallels;
  10,000 talents glossed against Herodian annual tax revenue (~900 talents/yr, Josephus Ant. 17.11.4)
- Ch19 divorce: Shammai-Hillel controversy on Deut 24:1; camel/needle is literal
  hyperbole (cf. b. Berakhot 55b elephant idiom), not a Jerusalem gate legend
- Ch20: day-labor market in the agora; lytron (v.28) is Matthew's only ransom-atonement term;
  Jericho at 240m below sea level on the Perean pilgrim route to Jerusalem
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

MATTHEW = {
  "18": {
    "1": '<p>The disciples\' question "who is greatest in the kingdom of heaven?" reflects the honor-precedence calculus fundamental to Mediterranean social life. Greatness was a finite, competitive commodity — one person\'s elevation implied another\'s diminishment. Patronage hierarchies, seating arrangements at banquets, and public greetings all encoded rank. Jesus\' answer directly subverts this logic by placing a child at the center.</p>',
    "2": '<p>Jesus calls a child (<em>paidion</em>) to stand in the center of the group — a deliberate visual argument before a word is spoken. In the ancient world children occupied the lowest rung of the honor hierarchy: legally without status, socially invisible except as potential heirs. Setting a child as the positive model inverts every assumption about greatness.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"Turn" (<em>strephete</em>) implies a directional reversal of trajectory — not gradual improvement but fundamental reorientation. "Become like little children" is not romanticizing childhood innocence but about structural position. A child had no claim on honor, no accumulated social capital, no standing to leverage. Entry into the kingdom requires abandoning status-seeking entirely.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Whoever humbles himself like this child" — <em>tapeinōsei heauton</em>, self-abasement in the sense of voluntarily accepting low social position. In a culture where public honor was fiercely defended and any slight demanded response, choosing the posture of the socially powerless was counter-intuitive to the point of seeming shameful. This is the kingdom\'s paradox: the greatest is the one who claims the least.</p>',
    "5": '<p>Receiving a child "in my name" transposes the social calculus entirely: to welcome the socially invisible is to welcome the one who sends them. The identification between Jesus and the vulnerable "little ones" (<em>mikroi</em>) runs throughout the discourse and climaxes in the sheep-goat judgment of ch. 25. Patron-client logic is replaced by a vertical identification — Christ with the marginal.</p>',
    "6": '<p>The <em>mylos onikos</em> ("millstone turned by a donkey") is the large upper stone of a commercial grain mill requiring an animal to drive it. Drowning weighted with such a millstone was a known execution method in the ancient world (Josephus records it, <em>Ant.</em> 14.15.10). The graphic image signals the gravity of causing the vulnerable to stumble (<em>skandalizein</em>).</p>',
    "7": '<p>"Woe to the world because of stumbling blocks" — <em>ouai</em> is a lament cry from the prophetic tradition, not merely a threat. The passive "they must come" (<em>anankē elthein ta skandala</em>) does not approve scandal but acknowledges its inevitability in a fallen world. The responsibility falls on the agent, not the world that produces stumbling occasions.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Hand and foot as things to be cut off invoke the imagery of radical surgery — Jewish and Roman audiences understood amputating a limb that would otherwise kill the body as rational medicine. Jesus applies this logic to moral life: no social relationship or habit that endangers eternal life is worth preserving. "Eternal fire" (<em>pur to aiōnion</em>) echoes the Valley of Hinnom (Gehenna) southeast of Jerusalem where refuse burned continuously.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The eye metaphor reinforces the surgical imperative: even the faculty of sight must be sacrificed if it becomes the pathway of destruction. In physiognomic ancient thought the eye was not merely passive but an active agent of desire. "Hellfire" (<em>geennan tou pyros</em>) is Gehenna, the perpetually smoldering Hinnom Valley refuse dump that became the standard Second Temple image for eschatological judgment.</p>',
    "10": '<p>"Their angels in heaven always see the face of my Father" — "seeing the face" of a sovereign is the technical idiom for having direct access to the king, reserved for the highest court officials (Esth 1:14; 2 Kgs 25:19). In Persian and Hellenistic court protocol, proximity to the royal face signified rank and favor. To say the angels of the "little ones" have this access is to declare their heavenly dignity counterbalancing their earthly invisibility.</p>',
    "11": '<p>This verse ("For the Son of Man came to save the lost") is absent from the earliest manuscripts (Sinaiticus, Vaticanus) and is generally regarded as a scribal assimilation from Luke 19:10. The commentary context flows naturally from verse 10 to verse 12 without it, and its absence in the best witnesses suggests it was not original to Matthew.</p>',
    "12": '<p>The parable of the lost sheep opens with a rhetorical question assuming a Palestinian shepherding context: flocks of one hundred were a standard viable unit for a family operation. Sheep were left on <em>ta orē</em> — the open hills — not abandoned but in temporary care, either folded in a communal pen or grazed by another. The shepherd\'s departure to seek one is a calculated risk, not recklessness.</p>',
    "13": '<p>The verb <em>chairei</em> (rejoices) is emphatic: the emotional intensity attached to recovery of the one lost exceeds even the settled relief of having the ninety-nine. Quantitative logic is deliberately upended. The parable\'s application to "little ones who believe in me" makes this joy divine: God actively seeks the vulnerable and the straying.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"It is not the will of your Father" — <em>thelēma</em> here signals settled divine disposition, not merely preference. God\'s will is that none of these "little ones" perish. In context, "little ones" are the socially marginal, the stumbled, and the lost — precisely those the community must not despise (v.10) or lead astray (v.6). The parable grounds community responsibility in divine character.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Take with you one or two more, so that every matter may be established by the testimony of two or three witnesses" — a direct citation of Deut 19:15. The Qumran community (1QS 5:25-6:1; CD 9:2-4) deployed the same Deuteronomy text for internal discipline, suggesting this two-witness procedure was already established Second Temple practice for sectarian communities. The escalation structure (private, witnessed, assembly) parallels procedures in both Qumran literature and m. Sanhedrin.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"Tell it to the church" (<em>tē ekklēsia</em>) designates the local community assembly, analogous to the <em>qahal</em> (assembly) of Israel in the LXX. "As a Gentile and tax collector" — social outsider status — is the practical result of repeated refusal, describing how the community now relates to the unrepentant, not a theological condemnation of the person\'s ultimate fate. The social boundary is precisely defined: the person is treated as one outside the covenant community.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"Whatever you bind on earth will be bound in heaven" — the binding/loosing authority (<em>deō/lyō</em>) granted to Peter at Caesarea Philippi (16:19) is extended to the community as a whole. In rabbinic literature <em>asar/shara</em> (Aramaic equivalents) designated halakhic authority: the power to declare what is permissible or forbidden and to include or exclude from community. Heaven ratifying earth\'s judgments signals that the community\'s disciplinary decisions carry eschatological weight.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"If two of you agree on earth" — the word "agree" is <em>symphōnēsōsin</em>, to sound together in harmony (root of "symphony"). The context is specifically the gathered community\'s prayer within the disciplinary discernment process. The two-person minimum recalls the two-witness standard of v.16; community discernment in accordance with Torah-procedure carries divine confirmation.</p>',
    "20": '<p>"Where two or three are gathered in my name, there am I among them" — m. Avot 3:2 states that when two sit and occupy themselves with Torah, the Shekinah rests between them. Jesus claims the same divine presence for gatherings in his name, placing himself in the role that the Shekinah occupies in rabbinic theology: the divine presence promised in community Torah-study is now promised in community gathering in his name.</p>',
    "21": '<p>Peter\'s question "up to seven times?" may reflect familiarity with the rabbinic tradition in b. Yoma 86b: a man who transgresses once, twice, or three times may be forgiven, but if he transgresses a fourth time he is not forgiven. Seven is Peter\'s generous extension beyond this threshold. Jesus\' response — "not seven but seventy-seven times" — effectively removes the counting mechanism entirely, making forgiveness structurally unlimited.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The phrase "seventy-seven times" (<em>hebdomēkontakis hepta</em>) deliberately echoes Gen 4:24, where Lamech boasts of seventy-sevenfold vengeance. Jesus inverts Lamech\'s vengeful arithmetic into an arithmetic of forgiveness: the same escalation dynamic applies, but in the opposite direction. There is no ceiling on forgiveness for the one who has received the infinite mercy the following parable illustrates.</p>',
    "23": '<p>The parable of the unforgiving servant is introduced as an analogy for "the kingdom of heaven" — meaning kingdom-norms. A king who audits his servants\' accounts is a standard image for divine judgment; the Ptolemaic and Roman fiscal systems created precisely this account-settling relationship between regional administrators and imperial treasurers, making the scenario immediately recognizable.</p>',
    "24": '<p>Ten thousand talents (<em>myria talanta</em>) is a deliberately fantastic sum. A talent equaled approximately 6,000 denarii; a denarius was a day\'s wage for a laborer. Ten thousand talents equals roughly 60 million denarii — 200,000 years of daily labor. The annual tax revenue of Judea, Samaria, and Galilee combined under Herod was approximately 900 talents (Josephus, <em>Ant.</em> 17.11.4). The debt is not just unpayable but conceptually staggering, representing an insurmountable moral deficit before God.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The standard remedy for insolvency in the Greco-Roman world was sale of the debtor, his wife, children, and possessions to recover whatever partial value was possible. This was legally regulated but economically brutal. The debtor\'s fall to his knees (<em>prosekynei</em>) and appeal for patience reflect the patron-client supplication posture; the master\'s compassionate release is a calculated act of radical grace within a system that had no structural obligation to offer it.</p>',
    "26": '<p>The debtor\'s promise "I will repay you everything" (<em>panta apodōsō soi</em>) is patently absurd given the scale of 10,000 talents. Yet the master cancels the debt entirely (<em>aphēken auton</em>). The Greek verb <em>aphēken</em> (released, let go) is the same root as <em>aphiēmi</em> used for forgiveness of sins throughout the Gospels, making the fiscal cancellation transparently theological.</p>',
    "27": '<p>The lord "was moved with compassion" (<em>esplanchnisthē</em>) — the visceral compassion language (from <em>splanchna</em>, intestines) used elsewhere for Jesus himself (9:36; 14:14; 15:32; 20:34). The king\'s emotional response before the debt cancellation demonstrates that forgiveness flows from character, not accounting. The full cancellation of 10,000 talents sets the scale against which the 100-denarius incident will be measured.</p>',
    "28": '<p>One hundred denarii represents approximately three to four months of a laborer\'s wages — significant but humanly manageable, utterly negligible against 10,000 talents. The forgiven servant\'s violence — "grabbed him and began to choke him" (<em>epnigen auton</em>) — exhibits the patron-client world\'s normal debt-enforcement logic, now grotesquely disproportionate given what the servant has just received.</p>',
    "29": '<p>The fellow servant\'s appeal is word-for-word identical to the first servant\'s original appeal to the master (v.26): "Be patient with me, and I will repay you." The verbal echo is precise and deliberate. The forgiven servant now hears the same words he spoke in desperation, yet cannot extend the patience he himself received.</p>',
    "30": '<p>The "debtor\'s prison" system existed throughout the Hellenistic and Roman world: a creditor could have an insolvent debtor imprisoned not to pay the debt (impossible in prison) but to coerce family members or patrons to pay on the debtor\'s behalf. The prison was a social lever on external networks, not a path to debt retirement — underscoring the irrationality of the unforgiving servant\'s action.</p>',
    "31": '<p>Fellow servants who witness the incident are "deeply distressed" (<em>elypēthēsan sphodra</em>) and report to the master. The servants\' grief signals that the unforgiving servant\'s behavior has transgressed recognizable norms — even within normal patron-client logic — not merely kingdom ideals. The community functions as a moral witness, parallel to the community disciplinary role described in vv. 15-17.</p>',
    "32": '<p>The master\'s second summons uses "wicked servant" (<em>ponēre doule</em>) — the language of moral verdict. "I forgave you all that debt" explicitly narrates what was done, forcing the servant to confront the scale of grace received. This is not merely administrative; it is making the servant face the nature of the mercy he spurned before pronouncing judgment.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"Should you not also have had mercy on your fellow servant, just as I had mercy on you?" — the grammatical form (<em>ouk edei se kai</em>) expresses logical necessity. Receiving mercy at the scale of 10,000 talents creates a proportionate obligation. The kingdom operates by a transformative logic: those whom God has forgiven incalculably are expected to extend proportionate mercy. The failure is not merely ingratitude but a fundamental failure to be reshaped by grace.</p>',
    "34": '<p>The master hands the servant to the "torturers" (<em>basanistais</em>) — a distinct category from jailers, suggesting physical interrogation to force revelation of hidden assets. The sentence "until he should pay all his debt" is, given 10,000 talents, effectively permanent. Jewish apocalyptic imagery of final judgment deployed precisely this kind of inescapable debt-settlement framework.</p>',
    "35": '<p>"My heavenly Father will also do the same to you if each of you does not forgive his brother from his heart" — the application closes the discourse. "From the heart" (<em>apo tōn kardiōn hymōn</em>) distinguishes genuine internal release from external compliance. The kingdom community\'s practice of forgiveness is not a legal requirement to be technically satisfied but a moral transformation expected of those who have received mercy at the scale of 10,000 talents.</p>'
  },
  "19": {
    "2": '<p>Jesus\' movement from Galilee to "the region of Judea beyond the Jordan" (Perean territory east of the Jordan, part of Herod Antipas\'s jurisdiction) follows the standard pilgrim route to Jerusalem that avoided Samaria. Large crowds following him through Perea were common at Passover season. The crowd\'s following and his healings establish the public context within which the Pharisees\' challenge in v.3 is designed as a test before witnesses.</p>',
    "3": '<p>The Pharisees\' question "Is it lawful to divorce one\'s wife for any cause?" is a technical legal probe referencing the Shammai-Hillel controversy over Deut 24:1. The phrase "for any cause" (<em>kata pasan aitian</em>) echoes the Hillelite interpretation: Rabbi Hillel read <em>erwat dabar</em> as permitting divorce for virtually any displeasure — even if a wife burned the food (m. Gittin 9:10). Rabbi Shammai restricted it to sexual immorality. Jesus is invited to declare for one school, which would alienate the other\'s adherents.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Have you not read that he who created them from the beginning made them male and female?" — Jesus bypasses the Mosaic concession by appealing to the creation order in Gen 1:27 and 2:24. "From the beginning" (<em>ap\' archēs</em>) is a hermeneutical move: the normative standard for marriage is not Mosaic legislation but the structure of creation itself. The Mosaic concession is explicitly framed as accommodation, not ideal.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The citation of Gen 2:24 ("a man shall leave his father and mother and hold fast to his wife, and they shall become one flesh") establishes the ontological foundation of marriage. "One flesh" (<em>mia sarx</em>) in the LXX denotes not merely sexual union but kinship solidarity — the bond that in Israelite culture carried the strongest obligation. Marriage creates this level of bond, superseding the family of origin.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"What God has joined together, let not man separate" — <em>ho theos synezeuxen</em> ("God yoked together") uses the language of a pair of animals placed under the same yoke. The passive implies divine action in each marriage. <em>Anthrōpos mē chōrizetō</em>: the prohibitive present imperative states a general rule. Jesus does not merely restrict divorce grounds — he reframes marriage as a divine act that human legal procedure cannot undo at its fundamental level.</p>',
    "7": '<p>The Pharisees counter with Moses: "Why then did Moses command one to give a certificate of divorce?" (Deut 24:1-4). The word "command" (<em>eneteilato</em>) is a slight misquotation — Deuteronomy 24 assumes divorce occurs and regulates its aftermath; it does not command or require a certificate. Jesus corrects this reading in v.8 by distinguishing Mosaic accommodation from Mosaic command.</p>',
    "8": '<p>"Because of your hardness of heart Moses allowed you to divorce your wives, but from the beginning it was not so" — <em>sklērokardia</em> (hardness of heart) is the LXX\'s standard term for Israel\'s covenant resistance (Ezek 3:7; Zech 7:12). Moses\'s permission is a concession to human moral failure, not a revelation of God\'s ideal. Jesus places himself in the position of announcing the Edenic order over the Mosaic accommodation — a claim of authority over the Torah\'s interpretation.</p>',
    "9": '<p>The exception clause "except for sexual immorality" (<em>mē epi porneia</em>) aligns Jesus closer to Shammai than Hillel but grounds the position not in halakhic reasoning but in the creation order. The word <em>porneia</em> has a wide semantic range including sexual immorality broadly, pre-marital unchastity, and possibly incestuous unions (cf. 1 Cor 5:1). The remarriage clause asserts that divorce does not dissolve the marriage bond at its fundamental level.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The disciples\' response — "if such is the case with a man\'s wife, it is better not to marry" — reflects the radical nature of Jesus\' position. In a world where divorce was a widely available male privilege (the Hillelite position was popular), removing this exit option made marriage seem prohibitively risky. Their conclusion is blunt social calculus: without easy exit, the risk of an incompatible marriage is too high.</p>',
    "11": '<p>"Not everyone can receive this saying, but only those to whom it is given" — <em>chōrein</em> (receive, contain, make room for) suggests capacity, not merely willingness. Jesus acknowledges that both celibacy and his demanding view of marriage are not universally given as vocations. The "gift" dimension of sexual ethics recurs in Paul\'s treatment (1 Cor 7:7), where both celibacy and marriage are designated as specific charisms.</p>',
    "12": '<p>Three types of eunuchs: those born so from birth (congenital conditions); those made eunuchs by others (castration performed on servants in royal courts — common in the Ptolemaic, Herodian, and Roman imperial households; Josephus describes eunuchs in Herod\'s court, <em>Ant.</em> 16.8.1); and those who have made themselves eunuchs for the kingdom (voluntary celibacy). The third type was unusual in Judaism — though the Qumran community may have included permanently celibate members. Jesus presents this as a calling, not a universal demand.</p>',
    "13": '<p>Children were brought to Jesus "so that he might lay hands on them and pray." Laying hands on children by elders or rabbis for blessing was practiced on Yom Kippur (documented in Soferim 18:5). The gesture invokes the patriarchal blessing tradition (Jacob blessing Ephraim and Manasseh, Gen 48:14). The disciples\' rebuke reflects their misapplication of the honor logic Jesus has been overturning throughout ch. 18.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Let the children come to me and do not hinder them, for to such belongs the kingdom of heaven" — <em>tōn toioutōn</em> ("to such") designates the structurally low-status, those without social standing to claim access. The kingdom belongs to those who arrive without leverage or inherited honor. Jesus\' reception of the children — contra the disciples\' gatekeeping — enacts the ch. 18 discourse concretely.</p>',
    "15": '<p>The laying on of hands and departure mark the completion of the blessing act. The children episode stands between the divorce discussion and the rich young ruler, framing the question of who receives kingdom access: not those with leverage or wealth, but those who arrive only in need, without social capital to claim entry.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"Good teacher, what good thing shall I do to inherit eternal life?" — addressing a teacher as "good" (<em>agathe didaskale</em>) was unusual; goodness was a divine attribute (b. Ta\'anit 4a: "none is good except the Holy One"). Jesus\' response invites examination of the greeting\'s implications. "Eternal life" (<em>zōē aiōnios</em>) is the eschatological inheritance of the age to come, the resurrection life of the righteous.</p>',
    "17": '<p>"If you want to enter life, keep the commandments" — Jesus begins with the Torah\'s own framework: covenantal life is bounded by covenantal obedience. The man\'s follow-up question ("Which ones?") suggests he expects a short list of essential commandments — a known rabbinic genre. Various teachers summarized the Torah\'s core: Hillel as the Golden Rule; R. Akiva as "love your neighbor as yourself"; Jesus in 22:37-40 as the double love command. Here Jesus cites the Decalogue\'s social commandments.</p>',
    "18": '<p>The commandments listed — do not murder, do not commit adultery, do not steal, do not bear false witness, honor your father and mother — are the second-table Decalogue commands governing human relationships (Exod 20:12-16; Deut 5:16-20). Jesus adds "love your neighbor as yourself" (Lev 19:18), the summary command that both Hillel and R. Akiva used to encapsulate Torah\'s social ethic.</p>',
    "19": '<p>The inclusion of Lev 19:18 alongside the Decalogue integrates the Holiness Code\'s social ethic with Sinai law\'s prohibitions. In Jewish interpretation, Lev 19:18 was understood to encompass one\'s whole obligation to fellow covenant members. Jesus\' citation points forward to his coming demand: the one thing lacking will test whether love of neighbor extends to the poor.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The young man\'s claim — "All these I have kept. What do I still lack?" — is not dismissed as self-deception. Jewish teachers took seriously the possibility of sustained covenant faithfulness; Paul similarly claims "blameless" Torah-observance (Phil 3:6). The word "lack" (<em>hysteroumen</em>) is his own formulation, signaling genuine moral seriousness. Jesus\' answer is not a correction of false self-assessment but a disclosure of where this man\'s particular attachment lies.</p>',
    "21": '<p>"If you want to be perfect (<em>teleios</em>), go, sell what you possess and give to the poor, and you will have treasure in heaven; and come, follow me." <em>Teleios</em> means complete, mature, fully formed — the word used in 5:48 ("Be perfect as your heavenly Father is perfect"). The call to sell everything targets this man\'s specific attachment, not a universal demand. "Treasure in heaven" is a well-attested Jewish concept for meritorious acts (Tobit 4:9; Sir 29:10-11; m. Peah 1:1).</p>',
    "22": '<p>"The young man went away sorrowful, for he had great possessions" — <em>apēlthen lypoumenos</em>. His grief signals genuine engagement with the call. The word "possessions" (<em>ktēmata polla</em>) refers to landed property — the primary form of wealth in the ancient agricultural economy, conferring not just income but social status and identity. Selling it would mean social death as well as financial loss.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"It is hard for a rich man to enter the kingdom of heaven" — <em>dyskolōs</em> (with difficulty). The statement is not absolute impossibility but a frank assessment of the structural problem wealth creates. In the patronage economy, wealth created networks of obligation, social identity, and self-sufficiency that worked against the kingdom\'s logic of dependence and generosity.</p>',
    "24": '<p>"It is easier for a camel to go through the eye of a needle than for a rich man to enter the kingdom of God" — the image is deliberately absurd, not a reference to a narrow Jerusalem gate (that identification is a medieval legend with no first-century attestation). The Talmud uses a similar hyperbole with an elephant in contexts meaning "something impossible" (b. Berakhot 55b; b. Bava Metzia 38b). Jesus\' audience would have heard deliberate comic impossibility.</p>',
    "25": '<p>The disciples\' astonishment — "who then can be saved?" — reflects the standard assumption that wealth was a sign of divine favor (Deut 28). If the apparently blessed wealthy cannot be saved, no one can. Jesus\' answer does not disagree with the premise that human effort cannot achieve salvation; it redirects toward divine possibility as the only ground.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"With man this is impossible, but with God all things are possible" — an echo of Gen 18:14 ("Is anything impossible for God?") in the context of Sarah\'s pregnancy. The allusion frames salvation as a creative act of divine power, not human achievement. The rich man\'s wealth becomes a category parallel to Sarah\'s barrenness: the obstacle is resolved not by effort but by God\'s power to do what is structurally impossible.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"We have left everything and followed you. What then will we have?" — Peter\'s question is honest inquiry in kingdom terms. The disciples have done what the rich young man could not. Their forsaking (<em>aphēkamen panta</em>) includes the same categories: home, livelihood, family networks. Jesus does not rebuke the question; reward language is present throughout the Sermon on the Mount and earlier mission discourses.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"In the renewal of all things" (<em>en tē palingenesia</em>) — a term in Stoic cosmology for the periodic regeneration of the universe, used here in an eschatological Jewish sense for the messianic renovation of creation. "The Son of Man sitting on his glorious throne" echoes Dan 7:13-14. The twelve disciples sitting on twelve thrones judging the twelve tribes of Israel positions them as eschatological regents over renewed Israel — a claim to royal function in the coming age.</p>',
    "29": '<p>"Everyone who has left houses or brothers or sisters or father or mother or children or fields for my name\'s sake will receive a hundredfold" — the list is identical to the categories of kinship and property that bound a person into the ancient household economy. To leave them "for my name\'s sake" substitutes Jesus as the primary loyalty-object replacing family and land. The hundredfold return and eternal life are the kingdom\'s eschatological economy.</p>',
    "30": '<p>"But many who are first will be last, and the last first" — the honor-reversal principle structuring chs. 18-19 (children, eunuchs, the poor) is restated as a general eschatological law. The parable of the laborers in ch. 20:1-16 will immediately illustrate this reversal with the equal payment of those hired last and first.</p>'
  },
  "20": {
    "2": '<p>The householder agrees with the first laborers on a denarius — <em>dēnarion</em>, the standard day\'s wage for agricultural and unskilled labor in Roman Palestine. The agreement is explicit and contractual: these workers enter the vineyard knowing exactly what they will receive. This detail is important for the parable\'s logic: the complaint in v.12 is not about breach of contract but about perceived inequity in what others received.</p>',
    "3": '<p>"He went out at the third hour" — approximately 9am in the Roman daylight-hour system. The <em>agora</em> (marketplace) functioned as the day-labor hiring center in ancient towns: men gathered there from early morning hoping to be engaged for the day. Day laborers had no steady employment and depended on being hired each morning; failure to be hired meant no food for the household that evening.</p>',
    "4": '<p>"Whatever is right I will give you" (<em>ho ean ē dikaion dōsō hymin</em>) — the master offers not a fixed sum but a just determination. The ambiguity is deliberate: these workers enter on the basis of the master\'s character rather than a negotiated contract. This distinction becomes central when the master\'s definition of "just" turns out to be more generous than wage-market norms would dictate.</p>',
    "5": '<p>The sixth and ninth hours (noon and 3pm) repeat the pattern of v.3-4: the master continues to find and hire throughout the day. The rhythm of repeated vineyard visits signals urgency — the harvest requires labor and cannot wait — and the master\'s personal attention to finding workers rather than delegating the task.</p>',
    "6": '<p>"About the eleventh hour" — approximately 5pm, with only one hour of daylight remaining. Finding men still waiting in the marketplace at this hour represents the economically marginal: those not selected in the earlier rounds. The master\'s question — "why do you stand here idle all day?" — receives their answer: "no one has hired us." Their waiting is not laziness but structural exclusion from the labor market.</p>',
    "7": '<p>"You go into the vineyard too" — the eleventh-hour workers are hired without negotiation, entirely on the master\'s terms. No wage is promised; they go in on trust. This positions them as the paradigmatic recipients of grace: they contribute the least labor, arrive last, and receive purely on the master\'s disposition rather than contractual right.</p>',
    "8": '<p>Paying wages at day\'s end was both Torah-required (Lev 19:13; Deut 24:15 — "You shall give him his wages on the same day, before the sun sets") and economically necessary for day laborers who needed the money immediately to purchase food. The instruction to pay "beginning with the last" reverses normal queue order and ensures the earlier workers witness what the last receive before their own payment.</p>',
    "9": '<p>Each eleventh-hour worker receives a denarius — a full day\'s wage for one hour of work. From a strict wage-labor perspective this is economically irrational. But the master is operating by a different logic: the denarius represents not payment for hours worked but provision for a household\'s daily need. The eleventh-hour workers\' families need food as much as anyone else\'s; the master\'s "justice" is sufficiency rather than strict proportionality.</p>',
    "10": '<p>The first-hired workers "supposed they would receive more" (<em>enomisan hoti pleion lēpsontai</em>) — a natural inference given that the late-hired received a full day\'s wage. Their expectation is economically rational within normal wage-market logic. The parable deliberately activates this expectation to expose the assumption behind it: that relationship with the master is transactional, and more labor deserves proportionally more reward.</p>',
    "11": '<p>Receiving the same denarius, the first-hired workers "grumbled against the master of the house" (<em>egongyzōn kata tou oikodespotou</em>). The verb <em>gongyzein</em> is the same word used in the LXX for Israel\'s wilderness murmuring against Moses (Exod 16:2; Num 14:2). The echo is likely intentional: the grumbling of those who have received genuine provision is rebuked in both contexts as a failure to recognize the nature of what they have been given.</p>',
    "12": '<p>"These last worked only one hour, and you have made them equal to us who have borne the burden of the day and the scorching heat" (<em>ton baros tēs hēmeras kai ton kausōna</em>). The complaint names real labor — midday agricultural work in Palestinian summers was genuinely brutal. The parable acknowledges the grievance without dismissing it; the response in vv. 13-15 addresses it directly rather than denying the premise.</p>',
    "13": '<p>"Friend, I am doing you no wrong. Did you not agree with me for a denarius?" — <em>hetaire</em> (friend) is a formal address carrying both cordiality and gentle reproach (used similarly in 22:12 and 26:50). The master\'s response begins with justice: the contract has been honored exactly. The workers cannot claim breach of promise; what they feel is not injustice but envy at others\' good fortune.</p>',
    "14": '<p>"Take what belongs to you and go. I choose to give to this last worker as I give to you" — the master asserts sovereign discretion over his own resources. <em>Thelō</em> (I choose) is the language of deliberate personal decision, not arbitrary caprice. The master\'s generosity to the last does not diminish what the first receive; it merely refuses to treat their contract as a ceiling for others.</p>',
    "15": '<p>"Am I not allowed to do what I choose with what belongs to me?" — the parable\'s theological core. God\'s grace does not operate on the zero-sum logic of comparative merit; what God gives to the late-called is not subtracted from the early-called. "Do you begrudge my generosity?" uses <em>ponēros</em> (evil eye), the Greek idiom for envy or stinginess (Prov 23:6 LXX; Sir 14:10). Envious calculation is incompatible with kingdom reception.</p>',
    "16": '<p>"So the last will be first, and the first last" — the reversal formula from 19:30 frames the parable as its illustration. The parable does not punish the first-hired; they receive what was promised. But the kingdom\'s logic refuses to translate priority of calling or length of service into proportionally greater reward. Grace cannot be earned by longer service; it can only be received.</p>',
    "17": '<p>Jesus takes the Twelve aside separately from the crowd as they approach Jerusalem — the third and final passion prediction is the most detailed yet. The privacy marks its gravity; pilgrims traveling to Jerusalem for Passover numbered in the tens of thousands, making the road buzzing with religious energy and political tension. Approaching Jerusalem meant approaching the center of the power that would produce the confrontation he predicts.</p>',
    "18": '<p>"The Son of Man will be delivered to the chief priests and scribes, and they will condemn him to death" — <em>paradothēsetai</em> (will be delivered) uses the same verb that will describe Judas\'s betrayal and the Jewish council\'s handing over to Pilate (26:2, 15-16; 27:2). The prediction specifies the two-stage judicial process: Jewish religious condemnation followed by Gentile execution.</p>',
    "19": '<p>"They will deliver him over to the Gentiles to be mocked and flogged and crucified" — the three verbs specify the Roman procedure: <em>empaizai</em> (mock), <em>mastigōsai</em> (flog with the Roman <em>flagrum</em>), and <em>staurōsai</em> (crucify). The Roman crucifixion process typically included a preliminary flogging that weakened the condemned. "On the third day he will be raised" (<em>egerthēsetai</em>, divine passive) is the resurrection prediction, using the same "third day" formula as 16:21 and 17:23.</p>',
    "20": '<p>The mother of the sons of Zebedee approaches Jesus with her sons to make a request. Mark 10:35 has the sons approach directly; Matthew\'s version involving the mother may reflect the social convention of using intermediaries or the family\'s collective ambition presented through the patron-appropriate channel of maternal advocacy. The "worship" gesture (<em>proskynousa</em>) is the standard supplication posture for petition.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The request — "say that these two sons of mine are to sit, one at your right hand and one at your left, in your kingdom" — reflects the political geography of throne honor. In Near Eastern and Greco-Roman court protocol, the right hand was the position of the highest-ranked official after the king, the left hand the second (1 Kgs 2:19; Ps 110:1). The kingdom they envision is a restoration-of-Israel scenario with Jesus as Davidic king and the Twelve as his court officials.</p>',
    "22": '<p>"You do not know what you are asking" — their vision does not include the cross that stands between them and any such glory. "Are you able to drink the cup that I am to drink?" — <em>potērion</em> (cup) as a metaphor for one\'s appointed fate, especially suffering and death, is common in the OT (Ps 75:8; Isa 51:17, 22; Jer 25:15). Their confident "we are able" is not necessarily hypocritical — they will share in suffering, but they do not yet understand what they are agreeing to.</p>',
    "23": '<p>"You will drink my cup, but to sit at my right hand and at my left is not mine to grant, but it is for those for whom it has been prepared by my Father" — Jesus affirms James and John\'s future suffering (James is the first apostolic martyr, Acts 12:2) while distinguishing his role from eschatological assignment. The reserved positions belong to divine disposition (<em>hois hētoimastai hypo tou patros mou</em>), not to apostolic petition.</p>',
    "24": '<p>The other ten disciples are "indignant at the two brothers" — their reaction is not moral superiority but competitive concern about their own standing. All twelve share the honor-precedence logic the request exposed. The episode occasions a foundational teaching about power structures within the community, not merely a rebuke of James and John.</p>',
    "25": '<p>"The rulers of the Gentiles lord it over them (<em>katakyrieōousin autōn</em>), and their great ones exercise authority over them (<em>katexousiazousin autōn</em>)" — both verbs carry the prefix <em>kata-</em> (down upon), signaling domination from above. The Roman imperial system was the obvious referent: a clearly visible chain of command from emperor through legates to local client rulers, each exercising delegated power over those below.</p>',
    "26": '<p>"It shall not be so among you" (<em>ouch houtōs estin en hymin</em>) — the present tense may be descriptive of how the community should already be structured. "Whoever would be great among you must be your servant (<em>diakonos</em>)" — <em>diakonos</em> is a table servant, one who waits on others at meals. In the honor-ranked world of the symposium, where seating position communicated status, the table servant occupied the lowest visible role.</p>',
    "27": '<p>"Whoever would be first among you must be your slave (<em>doulos</em>)" — the escalation from <em>diakonos</em> (servant) to <em>doulos</em> (slave) intensifies the inversion. A slave had no legal personhood; all labor and time belonged to the master. The highest aspiration within the kingdom community corresponds to the lowest social category outside it — a structural subversion of every ancient status system.</p>',
    "28": '<p>"The Son of Man came not to be served but to serve, and to give his life as a ransom for many" — <em>lytron</em> (ransom) is Matthew\'s only explicit ransom-atonement term. In Hellenistic usage <em>lytron</em> designated the price paid to redeem a prisoner of war or to purchase a slave\'s freedom. The phrase <em>anti pollōn</em> (in exchange for/in place of many) employs the substitutionary preposition <em>anti</em>. The "many" (<em>polloi</em>) echoes Isa 53:11-12 (the Servant\'s justification of "many"): the Son of Man\'s death is not merely exemplary but redemptive — a ransom that buys freedom at the cost of his life.</p>',
    "29": '<p>Jericho is one of the world\'s oldest continuously inhabited cities, approximately 240 meters below sea level in the Jordan Rift Valley. It controlled the main ascent route from Transjordan to Jerusalem. Pilgrims from Galilee and Perea traveling to Jerusalem for Passover regularly passed through Jericho, making the crowds following Jesus entirely natural. The city was prosperous — a tax-collection hub (cf. Zacchaeus, Luke 19) and the location of Herod\'s winter palace.</p>',
    "30": '<p>Two blind men sitting by the roadside (<em>kathēmenoi para tēn hodon</em>) — begging by major roads was standard practice for the disabled in antiquity, as traffic was the primary source of alms. Their cry — "Lord, Son of David, have mercy on us" (<em>Kyrie, huie Dauid, eleēson hēmas</em>) — is a public messianic acclamation. <em>Huie Dauid</em> (Son of David) is the royal-messianic title; the cry invokes covenantal obligation to show mercy as a Davidic patron.</p>',
    "31": '<p>The crowd\'s silencing of the blind men (<em>epetimēsen autois ho ochlos</em>) reflects the social logic of access control: petitioning a teacher while he moved through town with a large crowd was considered disruptive and beneath the teacher\'s dignity. The blind men\'s persistence — "they cried out all the more" (<em>ekraxan meizon</em>) — crosses the social boundary the crowd enforces, insisting on their claim to the teacher\'s attention despite their low status.</p>',
    "32": '<p>Jesus stops and calls them: <em>statheis ephōnēsen autous</em>. The stopping is deliberate — contrary to the crowd\'s gatekeeping, Jesus grants the disruption his attention. "What do you want me to do for you?" — the same question asked of James and John\'s request in v.21, creating a contrast: their petition for honor-positions is redirected; the blind men\'s petition for sight is granted. The kingdom inverts who receives audience.</p>',
    "33": '<p>"Lord, let our eyes be opened" (<em>Kyrie, hina anoigōsin hoi ophthalmoi hēmōn</em>) — the passive "be opened" implies divine action. The opening of blind eyes fulfills Isa 35:5 ("the eyes of the blind shall be opened"), a text describing messianic restoration, though Matthew does not cite it here explicitly. The request is physically specific and modest: they want to see.</p>',
    "34": '<p>"And Jesus in compassion (<em>splanchnistheis</em>) touched their eyes" — the visceral compassion term (<em>splanchna</em>, intestines) is used five times in Matthew (9:36; 14:14; 15:32; 18:27; 20:34), always for Jesus\'s response to human suffering and always preceding miraculous action. The physical touch crosses purity and social barriers. "Immediately they recovered their sight and followed him" — <em>akolouthein</em> (follow) is the discipleship verb; their physical following on the road to Jerusalem carries resonance beyond the literal.</p>'
  }
}

